b'' b'|' b'| i am somewhat familiar with the db measurements as they apply to' b'| electrical circuits i.e. it is the gain of (for example) an amplifier' b'| measured on a logarithmic scale. however, this requires that you have a' b'| reference value: i.e the ouput is +20db (e.g.) with respect to the input' b'| signal.' b'' b'<stuff deleted' b'' b'| what you actually talking about here is dbm and not db. however, the terms' b"| are used loosely by most people. ``dbm'' is power with respact to 1mw, whereas" b'| db is a ratio. now, like these two english statement:' b'|' b'| i am doing well.' b'| i am doing good.' b'|' b'| similarly, people usually use db for dbm. another common mistake is spelling' b"| ``db'' instead of ``db'' as you did in your article. see the ``b'' is for" b"| ``bell'' company, the mother of at&t and should be capitalized." b'|' b'| with highest regards,' b'| babak sehari.' b'' b'good gravy! decibels are all *ratios.* the question that remains in' b'any ratio is the reference unit used. sometimes, this will be a reference' b'power, such as milliwatt (given a certain circuit impedance which' b'should also be included in the fine print or known, like ohms' b'in an rf circuit of that impedance), leading to an accepted' b'notation of dbm. maybe it might be dbv, disregarding the impedance of' b'the circuit and power developed, using volt as reference *amplitude*' b'(rather than reference power). or, it might have an arbitrary or omitted' b'reference that is not included in the notation, leading to just plain db.' b"so. look at it this way--'db' has an implied reference while notation" b"such as 'dbm' has an explicit reference." b'' b'for power:' b'' b'db 10*log( p(measured)/p(reference) b'' b'for amplitude' b'' b'db 20*log( a(measured)/a(reference) b'' b"'b' is for bel, which is a standard term for a log ratio to the base" b"10, named after alexander graham bell. a 'deci' bel is of a bel." b'it has nothing to do with the bell telephone company except for' b"the common founder's name. the small 'd'/large 'b' is per si notation" b"convention. i don't know anyone that's been crucified for messing it up." b'' b'common references for audio are:' b'' b'0 dbm milliwatt across ohms' b'0 dbv volt' b'' b'0 vu (a zero on the vu meter) dbm (pro gear line level)' b'0 vu -10dbv\t(consumer gear line level)' b'' b'' b'often times, a power amp vu meter will be aligned using' b'the rated power of the amp as the db point. it is all' b'done to whatever reference is reasonable for the application' b'or moment.' b'' b'note that in a circuit with a given (and maybe unknown) linear' b'impedance, if the amplitude goes up so many decibels, the' b'power will also increase the same amount. this proof can be done' b"with the above two identities and ohm's law." b'' b'--' b'--------------------------------------------------------------------' b'dave medin\t\t\tphone:\t(205) (w)' b'ssd--networking\t\t\t\t(205) (h)' b'intergraph corp.' b'huntsville, al 35894\t\tuucp: ...uunet!ingr!b30!catbyte!dtmedin' b'' b'******* everywhere you look (at least around my office) b'' b'* the opinions expressed here are mine (or those of my machine)' 